column1: i lived through many stories and journeys and milestones and traumas yesterday. this is the first part of the rollercoaster. i left home early (pic 1) to get to iit to judge to the #poetryslam organised by the student literature cell (pic 2). from there
column2: i rushed to @indiehabitat to catch my @alphabetsambar peeps @quateelahmad @the_copper_chick and @rhetoricalwoman777 perform at the #storytelling event. i was also to perform
column3: to re record my telling of flamingos
column4: a piece that always taps into a tender
column5: vulnerable place in my heart. but the events of the week took their toll and i found myself crumbling midway (pic 3). they were nice enough to let me go back up and finish but this is an experience that shakes any performer. thankfully my next appointment was at one of my safe spaces. there
column7: where an artist may lean so far into their feelings and experiences that they're unable to function in their art. it gave me pause and perspective.

یادتون نره که بهترین راه تبلیغ ما خود شما هستید، پس اگه از برنامه خوشتون اومد، اون را توی گروه هاتون و برای دوستانتون به اشتراک بگذارید.

پادکست میتونه یه راه فرار از روزمرگی های زندگی، مثل آشپزی، رانندگی، تایپ و غیره باشه. مهمتر ازون، لزومی نداره یک پادکست در یک مرتبه گوش داده بشه. پادکست را میتونید خورد خورد در طول هفته گوش بدید و لذتشو ببرید. ❤️ 😊

column1: 307039;instagram;2018-10-08 08:34:39;FALSE;"so much muck has surfaced in the past few days with men in positions of power being accused of misconduct. i had a particularly interesting conversation with a friend who said ""men can't do anything these days without being accused of some sort of misbehaviour"".
and i think i have just the way out of this predicament.
no wearing low jeans showing off your designer underwear. and throw away the tight bicep displaying tees. lose the accessories (like yesterday). you'll seem like a good boy that way
column2: and good boys are unlikely to be picked out for bad behaviour.

column1: limit the number of drinks to two. not one sip more. or better still
column2: give up alcohol. teetotallers  have a 'good' reputation
column3: significantly reducing chances of vile women blaming you for inappropriate conduct.

column1: don't go any place alone where you see one or more women hanging out together. turn the other way

column1: 307159;instagram;2018-10-08 07:21:38;FALSE;"「praise the brave」では、性暴力被害者による「#metoo」の発信に対し、「#remetoo」のハッシュタグをつけリプライをする事を促す活動を実施します。
現在は、勇気を出して発信した「セクハラを中心とした性暴力被害のカミングアウト・#metoo」に対し、表立っては『放置』されているように見えてしまっている現状だと感じます。
もちろん各個人へクローズドのアプローチでのサポートの声は届いているのかもしれませんが、それは周囲からはみて取れず、被害者はカミングアウトしても孤立状態が変わらないという印象を生み出しているように思います。 「praise the brave」のメンバーでも、「#metoo」を発信するも極少数のリアクションしか得られず、
バックラッシュのリスクだけを抱えるといった体験を持ったものがいます。
そこで私たちは、「#metoo」と発信した個人のそれぞれの勇気を讃えて「#remetoo」とハッシュタグをつけてコメントを返すことで、３つの効果を生み出したいと考えています。
１、声が誰かに聞き届けられ、さらに好意的に思っている人間がいるということが声を出した本人へと伝わることで、少しでも本人を力づけられると考えます。
２、辛い時や必要な時に、当事者が掴める「手」を実際に見える形にする事を実現します。
３、「#metoo」について「#remetoo」の反響が集まることによって、当事者が見守られている存在だと周囲へ伝達し、

column1: 307184;instagram;2018-10-08 06:16:55;FALSE;"🌸 activism is the rent i pay to live on this planet ~alice walker & me 🌸
even if you think you are registered  to vote
column2: you can go to the link in my bio or usa.gov and enter your state. californians have until october 22 to register
column4: update your address or legal name. it is critical that we vote on november 6
column5: 2018. it is a vote for women of all races
column7: and a vote against misogynistic white males who could care less if you

column2: the majority of whom are white
column3: and some misguided women who support them
column4: may believe that they “do care” about women-

column1: but if it is between you or their position on the supreme court or seat in most any form of government or high powered corporate position- it’s been very clearly articulated in their own words
column2: that they will not acknowledge crude behavior nor will they ever
column3: ever accept responsibility or penalty for it.

column2: they will all support each other
column3: in case one day it is they who need protection from their victims finally speaking out.

column2: just re-watch the testimonies of #christineblaseyford and #brettkavanaugh for yourself
column3: and then listen to the incredulous and indignant rage from these “husbands & fathers”
column5: for having to even be bothered to address the concern:

column1: should a lifetime seat in our highest court
column3: who will inherit the power to decide what is legal for a woman to do with her own body
column4: when this judge has a history of disrespect and disdain for a woman’s body?

column1: shame on these senators and a plea to wake up to the women enabling them.  our first action is not simply to vote
column2: but to help other women and decent men
column4: discuss who to vote for and why
column5: to organize voting parties and send our first most revolutionary message- if not for all survivors of sexual trauma and oppression by these prehistoric good old boys

307196;instagram;2018-10-08 06:34:05;FALSE;i have been silently reading all the updates globally and now in india around all versions of #metoo. and some days, like today, i only feel a deep urge to do something in my personal capacity to push that narrative towards a change. but not by complaining and using social media to vent, but really trying to understand what is the root of this problem and how can we identify and cure that individually and collectively. because there is an absolute psychological disorder in the society we live in. some of the most educated people i personally know may give the best advice and try to be messiahs for others but are so naive and lack judgement when they have to protect women in their own life. the frustration is obvious amd absolutely justified, but the approach to heal this problem needs a change, not a monologue but a dialogue, not men vs women but men with women. this is not being feminist, its only and only about being better humans and understanding each other better. call me crazy for using different shades of optimism to solve a stubborn stinky problem, but i don’t know anything better either.;;en;#MeToo.;;;;;0;;amritahaldipur;Amrita G column1: 307212;instagram;2018-10-08 06:45:15;FALSE;"অবশেষে #metoo প্রসঙ্গে মুখ খুললেন মালাইকা অরোরা। অভিনেতা নানা পাটেকর ২০০৮ সালে ‘হর্ন ওকে প্লিজ’ ছবির সেটে তনুশ্রী দত্তকে যৌন হেনস্তার ঘটনা প্রকাশ্যে আসার পর তোলপাড় শুরু হয়েছে বলিউডে।
সম্প্রতি পিটিআই-এর একটা সাক্ষাৎকারে মালাইকা অরোরা বলেন
column2: আমরা এটা নিয়ে আলোচনাই করতে পারি। কিন্তু কাজের পরিবেশ সুরক্ষিত করার একমাত্র উপায় হলো হেনস্তাকারীদের চিহ্নিত করা। ৪৪ বছরের অভিনেত্রী আরো বলেন
column3: নারীদের নিজেদের সমস্যার কথা খোলাখুলি বলা উচিত। যখন কেউ আপনার জীবনের কোনো ক্ষেত্রে সমস্যা সৃষ্টি করছে
column4: আপনি সেটা নিয়ে মুখ না খোলা পর্যন্ত কেউ জানতেই পারবে না। আপনি যখনই বাড়ি থেকে বেরোবেন মাথায় তো এই চিন্তা নিয়ে ঘুরতে পারেন না যে আমার কর্মক্ষেত্র আমার জীবনটা শেষ করে দিতে চলেছে। আমাদের এটা বদলানো প্রয়োজন।

column2: বিনোদন জগতে কাজ করা খুব কঠিন কারণ যে মেয়েরা ফিল্ম ও মডেলিং ইন্ডাস্ট্রিতে কাজ করে
column3: তাদের সবাই সহজলভ্য মনে করে। এই ধারণা বদল হওয়া প্রয়োজন। একটা মেয়ে ছোট স্কার্ট পরে বা ধূমপান করে বলেই তার সঙ্গে যা খুশি করা যায় না। সে যা করে নিজের ইচ্ছেতেই করে। ইতোমধ্যে প্রিয়াঙ্কা চোপড়া
column11: বরুণ ধাওয়ান তনুশ্রী দত্তের স্বপক্ষে আওয়াজ তুলেছেন।

column1: কর্মক্ষেত্রে মালাইকা অরোরা বর্তমানে ইন্ডিয়া’জ নেক্সট টপ মডেল টেলিভিশন রিয়ালিটি শোয়ের বিচারকের ভূমিকা পালন করছেন। এ ছাড়াও বিশাল ভরদ্বাজের নতুন ছবির ‘হ্যালো হ্যালো’ গানেও তাকে দেখা গেছে।

column499: 'NN')];অবশেষে প্রসঙ্গে মুখ খুললেন মালাইকা অরোরা। অভিনেতা নানা পাটেকর ২০০৮ সালে ‘ হর্ন ওকে প্লিজ ’ ছবির সেটে তনুশ্রী দত্তকে যৌন হেনস্তার ঘটনা প্রকাশ্যে আসার পর তোলপাড় শুরু হয়েছে বলিউডে। সম্প্রতি পিটিআই-এর একটা সাক্ষাৎকারে মালাইকা অরোরা বলেন
column500: আমরা এটা নিয়ে আলোচনাই করতে পারি। কিন্তু কাজের পরিবেশ সুরক্ষিত করার একমাত্র উপায় হলো হেনস্তাকারীদের চিহ্নিত করা। ৪৪ বছরের অভিনেত্রী আরো বলেন
column501: নারীদের নিজেদের সমস্যার কথা খোলাখুলি বলা উচিত। যখন কেউ আপনার জীবনের কোনো ক্ষেত্রে সমস্যা সৃষ্টি করছে
column502: আপনি সেটা নিয়ে মুখ না খোলা পর্যন্ত কেউ জানতেই পারবে না। আপনি যখনই বাড়ি থেকে বেরোবেন মাথায় তো এই চিন্তা নিয়ে ঘুরতে পারেন না যে আমার কর্মক্ষেত্র আমার জীবনটা শেষ করে দিতে চলেছে। আমাদের এটা বদলানো প্রয়োজন। তিনি আরো বলেন
column503: বিনোদন জগতে কাজ করা খুব কঠিন কারণ যে মেয়েরা ফিল্ম ও মডেলিং ইন্ডাস্ট্রিতে কাজ করে

column4: and as a human being who believes in truth and justice. i have been left heartbroken and speechless by the toxic poison of misogyny. but today as i discussed with orion the g-rated version of the kavanaugh hearings i found my voice. i vow to raise both my son and daughter with integrity and accountability and honesty. and i promise to do everything i can to offer them a different america than the petrifying one that we are seeing before us today. i will be working with some amazing women on a photo project helping to get the vote out. i’m looking to gather a diverse group of women for portraits as we each speak our truth about why voting in the midterm election is critical. please dm me for more details if you’re interested in participating. let’s rise up and take back our voice! column1: 307294;instagram;2018-10-08 04:24:54;FALSE;"#inktober #inktober2018 #inktober7 exhaustion. i had indecision and did 2. 2 very personal ones... i'm not looking to argue the first. and any nastiness... results in me shutting off commenting. #metoo but i will talk about the second. my mother has multiple sclerosis. it is a brutal disease. it changed my outlook on life from an early age. and. has constantly created complicated feelings with my mom. she and i dont get along. never have. i love her
column3: but we get on like baking powder and vinegar. but
column4: seeing her suffer so much because of this
column5: made me bite my tongue. recently she has gone from remission to progressive. she is in a rough spot.  she is 5'9"" but 98 lbs
column6: and  has lost most of her muscle mass. she is fighting as best she can
column7: but it is a bone deep weariness.

column1: 307312;instagram;2018-10-08 04:33:09;FALSE;"this recommendation of a social media fast couldn't have come at a better time. i have been noticing a lot of negative feelings coming out lately and couldn't pinpoint it until late this week.

let's see if i can explain... starting with this whole #metoo initiative. people posting about their experiences with sexual assault and letting others know that they are not alone. i get it. i appreciated it and understood the importance of speaking out. i know that we need to stand together and stand up for ourselves. each time i read someone's story
column2: i am brought back to my horrible experience of sexual assault. it is something that i cannot seem to forget
column3: no matter how much i try. and the feelings of sadness
column7: guilt and regret are all still very fresh in my mind when i think of this experience. i hesitate to share because i don't want to trigger anyone else as i have been
column8: but maybe sharing would help with maybe finding some healing and personal peace. i am not sure

column1: i was 14 years old and made the mistake of trying beer at a friend's house. her 22 year old brother bought it for her and i and one other friend. i drank 8 beers that night. the 2 other girls went to bed and i wanted to follow them
column2: but was asked by the 22 year old to stay. he said we should go downstairs and i said i didn't want to. i remember repetedly saying no but was in no mindset to follow through so i ended up downstairs with him. i remember saying no
column3: and him not listening. i don't remember any other details other than him taking my clothes off
column4: then waking up in the middle of the night naked with multiple condoms on the headboard and him asleep next to me. i was hurt and ashamed. i got dressed and went and slept the rest of the night on the couch.

column1: i never told anyone. i was afraid i would get in trouble or lose friends. i blamed myself for drinking and lying to my mom about adult supervision there. one of the worst parts is that i found out that i was not the only person he did this to. i could have reported it and maybe prevented another friend from being hurt years later. column6: and my smile was back bigger then ever my summer was incredible i was refocused on my goals and ready to take on life and everything ahead. but life happened and i hit a really huge bump in the road i crashed and burned i've put on a brave face and tried my best... but i hit my breaking point this weekend starting with putting some really raw and emotional feelings in a letter. a lot of soul searching but today i got hit with something pretty upsetting i was accused of something i'd never do
column7: by a person i really don't even know. all because of jealousy? i'm not even sure pure vindictiveness i honestly dont know but it was incredibly upsetting
column8: i went to church a mess and i cried at church and i think god hit me... does he do that? but the messages i heard left huge mark on my heart today i know that a lot of things right now are out my hands and ive given it to god to do as he plans. the letter.... my emotions
column11: my dreams and goals right now its in his hands. i cried hard today i haven't cried that hard in a long time. i had to let go of someone maybe for short time? i hope. i reached out for advice it was little different facebook post then usual and it scared me but my inbox and news feed was flooded with support which made me cry harder but to be reminded how loved i am
column12: how people truly value and see me that... that sets my soul on fire that is going to fuel me this week to truly be the best version i can be.

column1: 307324;instagram;2018-10-08 03:05:10;FALSE;"how about leftover yam cake for breakfast? this cake is gluten free
column2: sugar free and dairy free!! (next time when i have hipsters asking for a cake with all the above requirements

column6: the ""scream"" actress said hollywood's battle against sexual assault in the entertainment industry is only skin-deep. ""it’s a lie. it’s a band-aid lie to make them feel better

column13: despite being one of the most outspoken members. “i just think they’re douchebags. they’re not champions. i just think they’re losers. i don’t like them

column21: calling it ""literally impossible” for the oscar-winning actress to be completely in the dark on weinstein's predatory behavior. the actress also renounced support of hillary clinton for the same reason.""

column1: 307404;instagram;2018-10-08 02:37:32;FALSE;"these last two months have been  challenging on numerous fronts
column2: but the have been incredibly sweet moments that have made it all worthwhile.  with the challenges of late being quite ill for the past two days
column3: i decided that i was in desperate need of some serious self-care.  lucky & sequoia didn't disappoint... they never do.  lucky
column4: who has a reputation of being the harder one to win over
column5: ran off an over eager dog that kept trying to herd me by grabbing my hand then positioned himself protectively between the dog and me and began licking my hand where the dog had grabbed it. as i laid across his back to give him an awed hug of gratitude
column6: sequoia placed her head next to mine
column7: held my wrist in her lips
column8: and closed her eyes.  neither one of them had displayed either of these behaviors with me before.  it was as if they knew exactly how to hold my heart in that instant.  as we left
column9: i was moved to tears with gratitude for their kindness and longing for the day in which they will join our family in their new home. ❤

column1: 307417;instagram;2018-10-08 02:47:47;FALSE;"the inktober prompt for today is ""exhausted."" i drew a woman who is exhausted. she puts up with so much and she works so hard. the news of kavanaugh getting confirmed felt like a slap in her face. it hurt. it brought up pain from her past. it made her feel angry and so very sad at the same time. but it also reminded her why she fights so hard. she fights for love and she longs for change. she may be exhausted
column2: but she defies it all by simply... pressing... on.

column1: 307423;instagram;2018-10-08 02:52:50;FALSE;"the indian actress whose public allegations of sexual harassment by a bollywood star is sparking a string of similar #metoo claims has filed a formal complaint
former miss universe contestant tanushree dutta first alleged in 2008 that multi-award-winning nana patekar behaved inappropriately towards her during the making of a romantic comedy the same year.

but emboldened by the global #metoo campaign – where women have shared accounts of harassment or assault – dutta repeated the allegations in a recent interview and on saturday went to the police to officially report the 2008 sexual harrassment claims. “dutta visited the police station last night and submitted a written complaint
column4: told afp. “we are investigating the case but right now
column5: it is not an fir (first information report
column6: or a formal investigation) but a written complaint about harassment incident

column1: she also alleged in the interview that filmmaker vivek agnihotri had behaved inappropriately towards her during the shooting of the 2005 movie “chocolate: deep dark secrets”. the actress said in a statement last week that she had received legal notices from both patekar and agnihotri
dutta said she had also received “violent threats” from the fringe
column2: far-right nationalist group maharashtra navnirman sena and has been hounded by a “smear campaign” on social media since reiterating her claims against the pair. “this is the age-old saga of survivors in our nation

column1: 307457;instagram;2018-10-08 02:21:21;FALSE;"today’s post was supposed to be the first time i posted a fun sunday confession. i wanted to confess a guilty pleasure or a secret about a behind the scenes picture
column2: but i can’t. my sunday confession is that i am so disheartened by the way our society treats women.

column1: without even touching on the kavanaugh ruling
column2: i have yet to come across a women that hasn’t been made to feel uncomfortable by a man. and in most cases has bit their tongue at the time and brushed off the incident after. i have yet to work a shoot where either the model was actively harassed while i was there or the model has opened up about past incidents. most of these sweet women have felt the need to arm themselves with either pepper spray
column4: or knives to feel safe. i personally have thought repeatedly about applying for a concealed carry permit. if i’m on foot
column5: i’m usually bogged down with the handful of bags that make up my kit and therefor and easy target. •

column1: it’s disgusting that we are driven to such lengths. it’s disgusting that we are made to feel as though our voices and experiences don’t matter. it’s disgusting that this society views our bodies as communal property.
i know that change won’t happen overnight
column2: and that it’s going to take a ton of work
column3: but sign me up. i refuse for this to be the legacy that i leave behind for the women who will come behind me to deal with. #timesup #metoo #theresistance •

column1: against that man on the street who won’t stop cat calling you.
against that partner who uses sex as a weapon and doesn’t understand consent isn’t just for one night stands.
against that boss who is sexually harassing you but you can’t afford to loose your job.
against that boy you woke up next to and you were too drunk to say no.
against every man that ever took advantage of you.
against the government that continuously reinforces and excuses this cycle of abuse and patriarchy.

as much as hashtags and instagram post help (not much but raising awareness is so important and we are so engulfed in social media these days!!) it is so important to have these conversations. when you see it
column2: say something! don’t tolerate this behavior and staying silent when you know your homies do this is not helping!

column1: it is your duty as a senator to listen to and represent your constituents. by confirming brett kavanaugh to the supreme court
column2: you have largely failed your constituents
column3: and therefore you have failed your job. in the past
column4: you have voted against equal pay for women
column5: you have voted to remove federal funding from sanctuary cities
column6: you have voted to increase military spending
column7: you have voted for a tax bill that essentially rips healthcare away from millions of people... and now
column8: you are confirming a lying predator to the supreme court. time and time again
column9: you have failed to listen to your constituents and to do your job. you should not be in office.

column1: no matter your motives for confirming kavanaugh– you are harming women
column3: and marginalized people everywhere and sending a message that we do not matter. it’s disgusting that you would confirm someone like kavanaugh to the supreme court just to maintain your proximal power from association with powerful white men. it’s disgusting that you would confirm someone so terrible just for the sake of voting by party lines and furthering your political party. it’s disgusting that you would even dare to say that you believe that ford was assaulted and that the #metoo movement matters
column4: yet you have the audacity to assert that ford was confused and you don’t believe that kavanaugh was the person who assaulted her (ford said she was 100% certain under oath; meanwhile
column5: information is coming out of the woodwork that point out kavanaugh’s lies). you either believe and support survivors or you do not. we see you and we see through your lies; do not act like you support survivors while you do not believe us and instead empower predators.

you will be voted out of office. or just do us all a favor and leave now.

column1: 307529;instagram;2018-10-08 01:25:25;FALSE;"i will start off by saying this is not an easy post for me to be writing.  this is something i have thought long and hard about making.
i am truly disgusted by some of the posts/photos i have seen by family members and friends over the past few weeks
column2: especially in the past few days.  these posts and photos are in regards to everything that has been going on in the political world and is in very bad taste. i can only think that none of them has  been a victim of sexual assault or knows someone who has been.  maybe they do not know someone who has attempted to or who has commented suicide.

column1: earlier this year some i love very much harmed themselves and i know someone who years ago took his life.  i personally have been in the darkest of dark places.
i have kept silent way too long with something that is very personal and embarrassing.  i can and will no longer be silent.

three years ago (when i still lived in napa) i was sexually harassed and assaulted by 3 men who i considered to be friends.  it was at a fundraising event and many people saw and did nothing.  i was humiliated but said nothing.  i kept silent because i was told it would ruin my repetition and career.  as i am writing this i am shaking and i  am in tears.

so to those of you making posts or sharing photos that have to do with not believing women who have been sexually assaulted or joking about committing suicide perhaps you will think twice about doing so.

column3: yet was a bystander to my meltdown and offered such kindness. @bef247 lent her humor and wit and empathy. and of course

follow and learn to be a climate reality leader.

column1: 307555;instagram;2018-10-08 00:50:35;FALSE;"so what now...? as a health and wellness practitioner i am lucky because my work is a non-partisan issue. white
column7: we are all subjected to pain
column10: suffering. as far as i can tell
column11: suffering remains the sole aspect of existence that is truly insusceptible to bias. she alone sees no color
column15: no god... and so i remain as committed as ever to improving the quality of all women's health
column16: even those i disagree with politically

column1: but i have come to realize recently that even this notion
column2: this idea of my fate being linked to the fate of all women
column3: is in itself a revolutionary thought.

column1: there are still many women for whom access to self-determination is only accessible to them through their association with the existing societal structure. through it they are guaranteed:
1) physical safety (think of the ""she's my sister/girl-friend/wife get out of being harassed"" free card)
dismantling the status quo would dismantle the very power structure they depend upon.
i say this not because we should condone it
column2: but because in the wake of the #metoo era
column3: the only way we are going to sustain the change we are so desperate for is to first change ourselves.

column1: and so if you are looking for what to do now
column2: i would invite you to follow my lead and shift your focus to dismantling the patriarchy within. - get loud and unapologetic

column1: - never laugh at jokes that imply that men are another child to take care of
- never let anyone claim your idea as their own
- never take the advice that when it comes to sex in marriage you should ""just do it"" (leave that to nike)
- remind your aunties and your grandmas that telling your story of sexual harassment publicly is not a cry for help but rather a battle cry
- ask for kisses or hugs from children

- pursue your dreams";;en;#metoo;;;;;0;;lindseythjackson;Lindsey T. H. column2: i worked at a domestic abuse and sexual assault shelter for women and children. there was an emergency hotline people could call to ask for shelter or just to talk them through their experiences
column3: help them set up safety plans
column4: help them come down from panic attacks triggered from their past traumas of abusers. i worked over night shifts at the shelter
column5: and calls would come in at all hours. one particular call that i keep on recounting lately was from a a woman who called the hotline
column7: sitting out on her porch with her shotgun
column8: in fear. she was afraid of her abuser coming to kill her
column9: finish the job he started years ago. she explained that he was a prominent figure in their community and that no one believed her when she reported him to the cops. that he had friends in the police and sheriff’s department. they laughed at her and told he she hadn’t been raped and abused
column10: that she was crazy. my job wasn’t to do much else than just listen and validate her feelings. i tried and help her come down from her anxiety and to help orient her. she asked me if i had ever been afraid of men. i said
column12: “really? you too?” i don’t know where this woman was from
column14: as these calls were anonymous. but just imagining this woman sitting in a chair on her porch at 2 am
column16: with a shotgun in her hands…she wasn’t crazy. she was trying to protect herself in the best way she knew how. the system had fail her over and over again.

when i was in middle school i hung out with some girls who were friends with another girl i never really hung out with. one day everyone was talking about how this other girl slept with an older man at a party and was lying about him raping her. my usual girlfriends were no longer her friend and were being soo mean.
my friends said she was a liar.
i left my friends and walked up to this girl and befriended her.
it ultimately didn't work out with girl and i

307599;instagram;2018-10-08 00:25:21;FALSE;it can feel overwhelming when we are constantly inundated with the violence and cruelty that exist in this world. it is easy to feel helpless and hopeless. ✨
the human race has evolved much faster than our biological capacities. technology has made it so that we hear about every injustice
column2: every atrocity. this awareness has benefits
column3: but it takes a tremendous toll.

column2: the simple act of shrinking our radius can offer us a reprieve. it is ok to give yourself a break. it can be healing to lose touch with the big picture for a bit to care for yourself

column1: simple face to face interactions with others in our community can remind us of our power. these connections can remind us of our common humanity.
there is a lot of power in the larger movements
column2: in common anger in the face of injustice
column3: in speaking up and fighting for what is right. but these expansive
column4: large scale actions must be brought into balance by focus on the work that lies directly in front of us. ✨

column1: this is the daily work of giving and receiving kindness
column2: patience and compassion. these actions and interactions are what renew us and restore our sense of hope.

column1: 307624;instagram;2018-10-07 23:58:38;FALSE;"self-portraiture is my therapy and i feel especially thankful to have it in my life right now. women are pushing through the darkness. it’s terrifying and challenging and necessary. we have the strength to do it even though it will not be without sacrifice as we’ve witnessed from dr. ford over the past few weeks. her strength and courage will guide and embrace us. we will come through this together. we will break free from the darkness. ✨✨✨✨✨✨ welcome to our #self_love_sunday_loop . i have teamed up with a group of other talented artists
column2: whom all share a passion for photography. we all agree how important photography is to us
column3: but also the importance of seeing ourselves in our art. we are encouraging each other to dig into our creativity through a series of self-portraits. we hope you will follow along with us on this journey. this week’s theme: {freestyle }✨✨✨next up is the lovely and talented @marisa.kraft . .

column1: 307632;instagram;2018-10-08 00:00:49;FALSE;"with all of the #metoo buzz there has never been a better time to learn moves that could save your life or a friends life one day from a attacker.⁣

i’m sore and bruised all over but this weekend i had the privilege of learning from nick hughes (look him up 😉) a true teacher and a master of realistic self defense. i learned so many practical moves and gained a lot of confidence. ⁣
bad things can happen anytime anywhere to anyone. you like to think it won’t... but it could.  it doesn’t hurt to be prepared ☠️🖤⁣

column2: i’ve heard stories of survivors— physically

column6: and physically. survivors don’t speak up because ptsd
column9: and society tell them they’re not worth it. they don’t speak up because they know they’ll be judged

column1: until you don’t understand what’s going on with them emotionally

the other has more to do with the assumption that the rules of the game might have changed radically since the beginning of neoliberalism and thus we are now facing an entirely different political context in which the framework of liberal democracy is largely incapable of providing any structural solutions to the emergency we face.
there should be little doubt that at least since reagan (though some would claim that this is a core feature of the federal state throughout history)

column1: 307725;instagram;2018-10-07 19:55:22;FALSE;"feeling a lot this weekend. when trump won the presidency
column2: i (like so many others liberals) was shocked. i couldn’t figure out how a country that was supposed to have my back could elect someone who was so blatantly sexist and had a known history of sexual assault (over a woman who was 100% qualified for the job). it shattered any illusions i had that women were valued as equal members of society. spoiler alert: we’re not. ▪️ today
column3: after 2 years of triggering and disturbing events
column4: i’m not shocked anymore. but i’m also not numb. i am fucking furious. ▪️ i’m furious that politicians care more about getting re-elected than doing the right thing. i’m furious that toxic masculinity has our county by the throat. i’m furious that white women are still siding with toxic white men
column5: rather than standing up for their sisters. ▪️ white women: i am you
column6: i know you. i know it’s scary to go against your husband or your father or your boss and stand up for what’s right. i know it’s easier to turn a blind eye to sexual assault than to face it head on. i know it’s terrifying to undermine men when your career is at stake. but we need you to do it. we all need to do it. otherwise
column7: we will always stay small. i’m looking at you @sensusancollins ▪️ #grabthembythemidterms

column1: a few months ago when i moved home
column2: i thought along the lines of “okay
column3: you’re healed from your rape now… focus on your mom’s diagnosis
column5: and going back to school for your science prerequisites”. right now
column6: i’m almost giggling at myself. ha as if healing was an end destination
column7: as if it was something i could check off a list and be done with. the universe definitely saw me going down that path and said “silly jackie”.

column1: politics this week and kavanaugh’s confirmation has brought up deep aspects of my assault that i was not aware were troublesome for me which has in turn revealed to me that healing is more of a process than it is an end destination.
could it be that when we’ve conquered one aspect
column2: when we’ve come to terms with one thing
column3: we are ready to heal what is next?

column1: maybe harder moments of healing do not discredit how far you’ve come/i’ve come…. maybe it means we are/i am strong enough for the road ahead
column2: the next speed bump and we/i could not have come to this point without all the other points before.

column1: this does not mean survivors are/i am sad all the time. this does not mean we are not/i am not “normal”
column2: functioning members of society. it does mean that there will be moments along the journey that prove to be more difficult
column3: and moments that we/i can invite in as opportunities to heal on a deeper level.

column1: i will share with you the opportunities the news has presented to me in the hope that speaking into the universe will kick start them into existence:
• may i go into the start of future relationships with a more open heart and with more trust. not all will hurt me as deeply as i’ve already been hurt.
• may i take a deep breathe before responding to anyone who has never walked these shoes because i’m in a position to educate if i come from a place of love.
• may i recognize my privilege as a white

• may i come to peace with the fact that i’ll never know all the details of my assault because of the drugs. my body knows exactly what happened and that is enough.";;en;;;;;;0;;jacquelinereilly_;// J A C K I E  R E I L L Y;;0;False;8;0;0;171;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/c7cfedb86a668f805a30dc3188558162/5D1D3A80/t51.2885-15/e35/42656343_479848489190939_3815414534484636420_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"a healing journey 🙏🏼

column1: this does not mean survivors are/i am sad all the time. this does not mean we are not/i am not “normal”
column2: functioning members of society. it does mean that there will be moments along the journey that prove to be more difficult
column3: and moments that we/i can invite in as opportunities to heal on a deeper level.

column1: i will share with you the opportunities the news has presented to me in the hope that speaking into the universe will kick start them into existence:
• may i go into the start of future relationships with a more open heart and with more trust. not all will hurt me as deeply as i’ve already been hurt.
• may i take a deep breathe before responding to anyone who has never walked these shoes because i’m in a position to educate if i come from a place of love.
• may i recognize my privilege as a white
• may i come to peace with the fact that i’ll never know all the details of my assault because of the drugs. my body knows exactly what happened and that is enough.";"a healing journey 🙏🏼

307747;instagram;2018-10-07 22:50:46;FALSE;ok here goes! as soon as i saw the #metoo talk advertised at #cheltlitfest i wanted to go. but i was hesitant. i didn’t want to go with anyone as i didn’t want to hear someone else’s opinions on #metoo after the talk. but could i face going alone? i left it right up until 2 hours before to book my ticket.  even as i sat down and watched everyone else arriving in pairs or groups i thought
column2: ‘is this still a good idea?’ but i’m so glad i decided to go and sit it out by myself. #metoo feels like a hugely personal thing but sat in a room full of strangers i was quietly comforted. the speakers were amazing and i wish it could have lasted longer; i could have sat for hours listening to them all. these 4 women
column3: all from different backgrounds and parts of the world coming together to discuss one seeming to be uniting topic. all of them inspirational
column4: all of them eloquent in their opinions and thoughts
column5: all of the calm and collected. and then came the audience questions. it’s always this bit that can go one of two ways. the first question/statement was by a woman who has written a book on her experience of being abused. ‘it’s taken me 5 years to heal’ she said. ahhh i wish for you and i that it only takes 5 years to heal. other questions came forward; all very interesting. one lady quite frustrated that her female friends didn’t identify as being a feminist.  i sat quietly thinking ‘am i a feminist?
column6: does me coming to this talk make me a feminist?’ ‘no
column8: no i uttered to myself’ but then i listened. how wrong was i about myself? yes i agreed with so many of the comments
column9: thoughts and opinions shared on the stage this evening but i’d never identified myself as a feminist. i  wrongly had the stereotypical feminist in my head of ‘we don’t need men in our lives fuck the lot of them’. but listening and thinking and hearing not just the stories from now
column10: today but also the stories from 100 years a go. and yes i do feel women deserve equality
column11: and yes i do detest that some men treat women as objects. and yes actually maybe i am a (dare i say it) a feminist. it was like a wave of empowerment
column13: and bravery hit me. well not too much bravery but perhaps that will.. tbc";;en;#metoo

column1: i am halfway around the world
column2: but recent events in the us leave me compelled to tell my story.

column1: i am a survivor of a sexual assault. i do not remember the day or even the month. i don’t remember what city i was in or the name of the hotel. i don’t remember my room number
column2: or how much i’d had to drink.

column1: i never wanted to tell this story!
from the minute it happened i thought that it must have been my fault. that i had laughed too loud
column3: worn too much makeup or curled my hair too much. maybe it was what i wore

column1: i even second guessed why i was wearing so little clothing to bed. in the privacy of my own hotel room.
i worried that it would end my career if people found out. i panicked about exposing one of the company’s “good ol boys.” so i said nothing.
people who mock trauma and say things like...”what neighborhood was it in? i don’t know. where’s the house? i don’t know. upstairs? downstairs? i don’t know but i had one beer
column2: that’s the only thing i remember!” 🗣

column1: these people are ignorant and they perpetuate the cycle of abuse. ask a veteran or an abused child...do we discount what they remember because they don’t know the street name?
which side of history will you be on?
i put the experience in a box
column3: locked it shut and tried to move on. but the body keeps score. it stores trauma and experiences. and sometimes they get triggered.
ayurveda and therapy help me move these experiences out of my body and mind so that i can live whole heartedly
column4: in spite of experiences like this. ✨✨✨✨

column1: we are having a human experience.
there is more in this life for us. we should expect more from our leaders. 🙏🏽 #namaste #metoo #believesurvivors #yoga #meditation #healing #trauma #vote #getoutandvote";;en;#namaste

column1: 307842;instagram;2018-10-07 21:40:08;FALSE;"another great day today starting with my mum waking me up (it’s always lovely to wake up to someone smiling at you!) for us to go for breakfast at one of our fave cafes in swansea: the junction just before mumbles on the seafront. i’ve done a split shift in work and had a wee sit down with the locals in my break and had such a giggle. i made a best friend
people and interaction really lifts my mood
column2: particularly those i come across in pubs.

column1: i absolutely loved being in work last night on an amazing busy shift with a great band and slept so soundly that i woke up with my bed still made with my blankets at the bottom. had a couple of flashes of nightmares as i was waking up but the feeling of comfort and home and knowing i’m not alone here has started to help quieten them down as i can focus on that feeling.

column4: orientations etc. most importantly..i felt like i needed to be here for my fellow black womxn. we live in a society where black girls are over-policed and over-sexualized at every turn. literally from our hair to our clothes to our bodies. a lot of black girls are raised thinking their bodies make them a hoe
column7: etc. to see us actively owning our bodies so boldly is truly revolutionary. even as adults
column8: black girls constantly are denied the right to be sexual beings and that needs to change. it was truly refreshing to be apart of this experience and see so many black womxn and woc walking in their light with no shame. i can’t wait to be back next year 👏🏾 and remember girls

column1: 307906;instagram;2018-10-07 20:54:02;FALSE;"being a survivor of sexual abuse can leave you feeling isolated and alone. this is one of the hardest effects of abuse. .
this is the purpose of my book. to break the illusion that are are alone. and to help you understand the strength that you indeed have. .
each one of us was given the strength to endure what we have endured. .
i see you. and i believe in your light. ✨

column1: 307917;instagram;2018-10-07 20:57:43;FALSE;"‪today my thoughts are still very heavy in my head. my whole body numb
column2: and my heart in two— bleeding out into my stomach; as hurt
column3: anger and disappointment run through my blood
column4: burning like an inferno in my veins. hearing of brett kavanaugh’s confirmation has shattered every fiber within me to its very core
column5: and it has done the same for millions more across our nation. the u.s senate and supreme court have lost all integrity
column6: and have really put my hope for humanity to the test.‬

column1: ‪to all the survivors of sexual harassment and assault out there today
column2: who have been brought to your knees in agony— i am with you
column5: and i understand because i too have gone through it myself. please know you are loved
column8: and that none of this is ever your fault!‬

column1: ‪to dr. christine blasey ford— it is with tears in my eyes that i thank you for your astounding courage and strength. your testimony may not have changed the outcome
column2: but it did change the country by ‬giving other survivors the courage and strength to bring their stories and their voices out of the shadows and into the light
column3: and to let them know they’re not alone.

column1: ‪to every senator who voted yes on kavanaugh and handed him this seat— shame on you! and the fact that some of you were women (susan collins) who turned a blind eye to this issue
column2: even after ford ‬stood up to the senate committee describing in detail the most painful experience of her life is ‪disgraceful!‬

column1: ‪kavanaugh is not only a danger to our nation due to being accused of sexual assault and enabling men who harm women
column2: but because‬ he will shape civil and constitutional rights jurisprudence in the country for decades
column3: undermining basic rights and freedoms. he poses a threat to women’s reproductive rights

column1: 307928;instagram;2018-10-07 21:03:16;FALSE;"we just got out from the picture place. the guy was very touchy feely. he actually had the nerve to say that we were taking too long to get dressed and yelled at us saying

column4: but he works with children all day so we want this man fired. as usual we are in high spirits
column5: but we were honestly really bothered during the situation.

column1: 307932;instagram;2018-10-07 21:04:22;FALSE;"he gaslighted me to the point of breakdown and then proceeded to insist for sex. i had nothing in me left to even say no... so i let him have me.
when i finally reached out to the victims services in sudbury
column2: my worker did not hesitate to validate me and confirm that i was not over reacting
column3: that this was 100% assault. i finally chose to take an other step further and go to the police and even the male officer and the male investigator immediatly confirmed this was assault.

column1: i am still trying to ""detox"" from what he put me through (not to mention a few other things he did). if you feel invalid or crazy for feeling the way you do just because you feel your assault wasn't ""violent enough""
column2: let me remind you that assault is assault and no one has the right to compare your assault to an other. you are absolutly right to feel upset even if you don't have physical scars. your body was still disrespected
column3: you were still taken advantage of
column4: you were still stripped of a choice. you are rational to feel like you do and even grieve.

column1: you are not crazy. you are valid. enough gaslighting.
this is why we also need good sex ed that teaches and enforces consent so that people can understand what may be being done to them.

column1: 307934;instagram;2018-10-07 21:04:36;FALSE;"i wish i could say most of my childhood and moving into my teenage years was a blur
i remember more than i wish i did some days
column2: and it serves as a a reminder to keep fighting for myself & my girls.

column1: recent events have weighed heavily on my heart.
i hate politics. i’ll just leave it at that
column2: because once that door is opened
column3: it can’t be easily shut again.

column1: coming from a survivor—not a victim
column2: it’s easy to just shut the box that is the pain
column3: suffering and trauma of being assaulted
column4: shove it in the back of your brain with the memories you don’t care to think about

column2: it was easy to shut up and never talk about it because fear of judgement and ridicule
column4: is still the situation most women are dealing with.

column2: i’ve been able to work through most of it
column3: learn that ugly things happen sometimes
column4: that we can’t control everything in life & how important it is to forgive for our own inner peace.

column1: i’ve been able to grow into a beautiful
i’ve been able to create a life for my girls that will never be the struggle
column4: i work as hard as i need to so that i’m able to give them a life they deserve.

column2: and more forgiving over the last year
column3: because we truly never know what hell others may be going through or have walked through.

column1: kindness is a language everyone can understand. speak it
column2: always. & please remember you’re not a victim for sharing your story & your truth. you’re a survivor
column3: and you never know who might need your love

column2: i’ve been able to work through most of it
column3: learn that ugly things happen sometimes
column4: that we can’t control everything in life & how impoant it is to forgive for our own inner peace.

column1: i’ve been able to grow into a beautiful
i’ve been able to create a life for my girls that will never be the struggle
column4: i work as hard as i need to so that i’m able to give them a life they deserve.

column2: and more forgiving over the last year
column3: because we truly never know what hell others may be going through or have walked through.

column1: kindness is a language everyone can understand. speak it
column2: always. & please remember you’re not a victim for sharing your story & your truth. you’re a survivor
column3: and you never know who might need your love

column2: and many elected officials beleive their voices don't matter. this will only change when women everywhere collectively stand up and say #enoughisenough. sign up on my website at www.votejenlunsford.com/get-involved and/or email us at colin@votejenlunsford.com. we have a wide variety of volunteer opportunities for people of all experience levels. #metoo #cancelkavanaugh #stopkavanaugh #rainn;;en;#enoughisenough.

column1: 307980;instagram;2018-10-07 20:19:10;FALSE;"you can recognize survivors of abuse by their courage. when silence is so very inviting
column2: they step forward and share their truth so others know they aren't alone. #metoo i was a victim of adam croasdell and will not be silenced
column3: threatened or shamed as a survivor for his actions anymore by him or whomever he has help him whether fans or friends he enlists. in november our joint interviews will be airing stateside. we will be sharing our experiences as a survivor of his abuse
column4: pictures to videos in conjunction and the various methods he used to try and silence us. i’m one of five women who have spoken up and been interviewed if adam croasdell has physically or mentally abused you or harassed your under multiple instagrams whether alone or with fans or his friends please come forward with hashtag #adamcroasdellabusedmetoo we would like to have you interviewed and speak out  against him to stop him from silencing another woman if you’re scared and have any chat logs
column7: audios or pictures we will take those to if you prefer to not be named but still want to help. your safety is more important and adam has a history of bullying and harassing women whether by internet or outside of it it does not matter if it happened on or offline. there are also six photographers who are going to interview and sue him for violating their copyrights
column8: harassment and vandalism of their work which he did under multiple instagrams if he’s done that to you to please let us know we will give you the information for that process use #adamcroasdellvandalized thank you for your help and supporting and stopping adam from vandalizing photographers work and other women from being hurt by this animal. if we stay silent we empower abusers creating more women to be victims. we need to support survivors instead of shaming or blaming them because a celebrity or person in power commits these atrocities.

column2: & my heart is so full. it’s easy to feel grateful at times like this
column3: but gratitude works its best magic when the going gets tough. cultivating gratitude is a powerful practice for me & i know from personal experience it is possible to choose gratitude even in the midst of deep suffering. i am grateful for the tough conversations we have been having this week about sexual assault & for the courage of women like dr. ford who so bravely add their voice to this tidal wave of expanding light & consciousness. and yes
column4: i feel hopeful in spite of the outcome. more women (&men) are finding the courage to speak the truth about sexual violence
column6: and our collective voice is growing louder by the day. always remember

column1: 307990;instagram;2018-10-07 20:22:22;FALSE;"@pregnant_then_screwed posted about how it's a year ago that the #metoo movement started. i commented on her post and have been thinking about it over dinner.
i am so thankful to the brave women who came forward a year ago
column2: who started #metoo and to all the women who have bravely shared their #metoo stories. .

column1: i think the movement has led to a reframing of women's experiences. helped women recognise their own experiences amd realise that discrimination and violation doesn't have to be  and should not be another part of daily life we have to put up with. .

i didn't really see myself as  much of a feminist before the #metoo movement. but i definitely do now.  and even though i don't feel brave enough to share my #metoo stories publically i feel empowered by the women who have.

and i know it feels like things are right back to square one or worse with the sickening result of the kavanaugh case. but they aren't. because when women find their voice and feel empowered to share their stories nothing can stop us. and the more of us who join the conversation
column2: even if it's just amongst our own friends
column3: the louder that voice becomes. and we will be heard.
